{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0cd07ad6-c76f-4db1-a0bf-7f9dc9af01a6","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it watches for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will re-execute all tests whenever you save a change to any `.cs` or project file. To focus on just your failing test, add a filter:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\n**About your failing test:** the `RemoveStock` method (line 37) subtracts without checking availability. It needs a guard to throw when `quantity` exceeds current stock. Once you start the watcher, fix `RemoveStock` and save — the test will re-run automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"02d0e46a-a79c-479b-97d9-b3def4d75530","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload functionality.\n\nLet me check what's available. Since this is .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the `dotnet test --hotreload` feature should be available. Actually, let me think about this more carefully.\n\nFor .NET test projects, the way to do hot reload is with `dotnet watch test` which will watch for file changes and re-run tests automatically. But with Microsoft.Testing.Platform in .NET 10, there might be a `--hotreload` flag directly on `dotnet test`.\n\n\nI'm weighing the two main approaches here: `dotnet watch test` is the traditional, well-established method for watching and re-running tests, while `dotnet test --hotreload` might be available with this newer setup. I'll recommend `dotnet watch test` as the primary approach since it's reliable and widely supported, but I should also mention the `--hotreload` flag as a potential alternative with Microsoft.Testing.Platform.","outputTokens":546,"requestId":"703C:1A5086:C4736C:E34AE